{{Infobox academic | name = David Rogers Chesnutt | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1940<!-- {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | birth_place = [[Athens, Alabama]], United States | death_date = December 15, 2014<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = [[Hardwick, Vermont]], United States | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | alma_mater = [[University of Alabama]], [[Auburn University]], [[University of Georgia]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = ''The Papers of [[Henry Laurens]]'' | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = Elizabeth H. Dow<ref name='legacy'/> | children = }} '''David Rogers Chesnutt''' (1940 – December 15, 2014) was an American historian and editor.
==Life== Chesnutt was born in Athens, Alabama, and earned academic degrees at [[University of Alabama]] (1962), [[Auburn University]] (1967) and the [[University of Georgia]] (1973).<ref name='sedit'>{{cite web|url=https://listserv.umd.edu/cgi-bin/wa?A2=ind1412&L=sedit-l&P=742 |title=SEDIT-L archives - December 2014 (#7) |publisher=Listserv.umd.edu |date=2014-12-15 |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref>
Chesnutt was in the History Department at the University of South Carolina for 35 years as Research Professor. His major work was ''The Papers of [[Henry Laurens]]'', serving as Associate Editor and then Editor. As part of that project he was influential in moving the [[scholarly editing]] project to digital technologies, which was ground-breaking at the time.<ref name='sedit'/>
For more than two decades Chesnutt served on the [[South Carolina Historical Records Advisory Board]].<ref name='sedit'/> He was an important figure in the foundation and early development of the [[Text Encoding Initiative]] and active in the [[Association for Computers and the Humanities]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Syd Bauman-7 |url=http://tei-l.970651.n3.nabble.com/David-R-Chesnutt-td4026727.html |title=tei-l - David R. Chesnutt |publisher=Tei-l.970651.n3.nabble.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tei.oucs.ox.ac.uk/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/PREFS.html |title=Appendix G Prefatory Notes - The TEI Guidelines |publisher=Tei.oucs.ox.ac.uk |date=2015-04-06 |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref>
In 2005 Chesnutt was awarded the [[Order of the Palmetto]], [[South Carolina]]'s "highest civilian honor for extraordinary lifetime achievement and service to the state and nation".<ref name='shrab'>{{cite web |url=http://shrab.palmettohistory.org/chesnutaward.htm |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20150213191615/http://shrab.palmettohistory.org/chesnutaward.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2015-02-13 |title=Order of the Palmetto Presented to David Chesnutt |publisher=Shrab.palmettohistory.org |date=2005-03-14 |accessdate=2015-07-01 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://shrab.palmettohistory.org/chesnuttremarks.htm |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20150213191835/http://shrab.palmettohistory.org/chesnuttremarks.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2015-02-13 |title=Remarks Delivered by David R. Chesnutt on being awarded the Governor’s Order of the Palmetto |publisher=Shrab.palmettohistory.org |date=2005-03-14 |accessdate=2015-07-01 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Haynie |first=Rachel |url=http://www.thecolumbiastar.com/news/2005-03-25/News/005.html |title=Henry Laurens scholar receives Order of the Palmetto &#124; www.thecolumbiastar.com |publisher=Columbia Star |date=2005-03-25 |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref>
Chesnutt died in [[Hardwick, Vermont]], on December 15, 2014, of [[throat cancer]].<ref name='legacy'>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thestate/obituary.aspx?pid=173546020 |title=David Rogers Chesnutt Obituary: View David Chesnutt's Obituary by The State |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref><ref>http://www.documentaryediting.org/wordpress/?p=1975</ref>
==Awards== * The Distinguished Service Award (with [[Charles Cullen (editor)]]) from the [[Association for Documentary Editing]], 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentaryediting.org/wordpress/?page_id=16 |title=Distinguished Service Award &#124; The Association for Documentary Editing |publisher=Documentaryediting.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> * The [[Lyman H. Butterfield]] Award from the [[Association for Documentary Editing]], 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentaryediting.org/wordpress/?page_id=14 |title=Lyman H. Butterfield Award &#124; The Association for Documentary Editing |publisher=Documentaryediting.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> * The [[Julian P. Boyd]] Award from the [[Association for Documentary Editing]], 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.documentaryediting.org/wordpress/?page_id=12 |title=Julian P. Boyd Award &#124; The Association for Documentary Editing |publisher=Documentaryediting.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> * The [[Order of the Palmetto]] from the [[Governor of South Carolina]] 2005.<ref name='shrab'/>
