{{see|1st millennium BC|List of Bronze Age states|List of Classical Age states}} [[File:World in 500 BCE.png|thumb|400px|Overview map of the world in the mid 1st millennium BC, color-coded by cultural stage: {{legend|#FFFF00|Palaeolithic or Mesolithic hunter-gatherers}} {{legend|#800080|nomadic pastoralists}} {{legend|#00FF00|simple farming societies}} {{legend|#FF8040|complex farming societies/chiefdoms}} {{legend|#8080FF|state societies}} {{legend|#804000|empires}}]] {{Iron Age}} {{synthesis|date=January 2018}}
The '''Iron Age''' is an archaeological age, the last of the [[three-age system]] of [[Old World]] prehistory. It follows the [[Bronze Age]], in the [[Ancient Near East]] beginning c. 1200 BC, and in [[Iron Age Europe|Europe]] beginning after c. 800 BC. It is taken to end with the beginning of [[Classical Antiquity]], in about the 6th century BC, although in Northern Europe, the [[Germanic Iron Age]] is taken to last until the beginning of the [[Viking Age]], c. AD 800.
The term "Iron Age" is mostly limited to [[Iron Age Europe|Europe]] and the [[Ancient Near East|Near East]] and the [[Iron Age India|Indian subcontinent]], although West Africa also has some iron metallurgy, beginning with the [[Nok culture]] c. 550 BC and spread by the [[Bantu expansion]]. There are also cast iron artefacts [[History of metallurgy in China|in China]] from about 500 BC, but use of iron was minimal, and the Bronze Age in China is usually extended to the beginning of the classical period ([[Qin dynasty]]).
