{{Infobox academic | name = Martin Daunton | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|FRHistS|size=100%}} | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1949|02|07}} | birth_place = [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = British | spouse = {{marriage|Claire Gobbi|1984}} | alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[University of Nottingham]] | [[University of Kent]] | [[University of Cambridge]]}} | discipline = History | sub_discipline = [[Economic history]] | workplaces = {{unbulleted list | [[University of Durham]] | [[University College London]] | [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]]}} }}
'''Martin James Daunton''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|FRHistS}} (born 14 February 1949) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[academic]] and [[historian]]. He was [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], between 2004 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/makinghistory/resources/interviews/Daunton_Martin.html |title=Interview with Professor Martin Daunton - Making History |publisher=History.ac.uk |date=19 May 2008 |accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.trinhall.cam.ac.uk/about/people/officers/detail.asp?ItemID=1887 | title=Master Martin Daunton | work=[[Trinity Hall, Cambridge|Trinity Hall]] | accessdate=30 September 2014 | author=Daunton, Martin}}</ref>
Daunton is the son of Ronald James Daunton and Dorothy ''née'' Bellett. He was educated at [[Barry Comprehensive School|Barry Grammar School]] before going to the [[University of Nottingham]] where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1970. He studied further at the [[University of Kent]] [[PhD]] 1974 and received the degree of [[LittD]] from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 2005.
In 1984, he married Claire Gobbi.
